# CRITICAL CONSTRAINTS & DEPENDENCIES

[CONSTRAINT:Ollama_Version_Identity]
MUST: Windows IDE Ollama version = Ubuntu Worker 1 Ollama version
Impact: Code generation consistency across both systems
Enforcement: Version check on startup + periodic sync
Failure_Mode: Disable code generation, show warning

[CONSTRAINT:SSH_Authentication]
MUST: SSH key-based auth to Worker 1 (ubuntu-atlas-01)
Impact: Secure, passwordless remote script execution
Setup: User provides SSH key path in IDE config
Failure_Mode: Right pane unavailable, local-only mode

[CONSTRAINT:Ollama_Service_Availability]
MUST: Local Ollama running (localhost:11434)
Impact: Code completion/generation features
Failure_Mode: Warn user, disable AI features, continue with file editing

[CONSTRAINT:Git_Availability]
Should: Git installed on Windows + Ubuntu
Impact: Version control operations
Failure_Mode: Warn user, disable git UI, continue with file editing

---

# KEY ARCHITECTURAL DECISIONS

**Decision 1: Dual-Pane Design (Left=Local, Right=Remote)**
Rationale: Allows simultaneous development + monitoring of Worker 1 environment
Benefit: User can see results of script execution on Worker 1 in real-time
Alternative: Single pane + separate Worker 1 window (rejected: context-switching overhead)

**Decision 2: Shared Ollama Version Requirement**
Rationale: Ensures reproducible code generation across Windows IDE and Ubuntu Worker 1
Benefit: User can apply same prompt locally or remotely, get consistent code
Alternative: Separate Ollama instances (rejected: inconsistent outputs, confusing)

**Decision 3: Script_Execution_Engine with Local + Remote Dispatch**
Rationale: IDE manages both local and remote execution from single interface
Benefit: Single UI for debugging + deploying scripts
Alternative: Separate local IDE + remote SSH client (rejected: complex workflow)

**Decision 4: HTTP REST API Backend (IDE_Backend_Windows)**
Rationale: Separates concerns, enables future remote IDE access
Benefit: Frontend can be web-based or Electron, backend reusable
Alternative: Direct IPC (rejected: less flexible, platform-specific)

